               J and Gauci, Vincent",
  abstract  = "AbstractWetland‐adapted trees are known to transport
               soil‐produced methane (CH4), an important greenhouse gas to the
               atmosphere, yet seasonal variations and controls on the
               magnitude of tree‐mediated CH4 emissions remain unknown for
               mature forests. We examined the spatial and temporal variability
               in stem CH4 emissions in situ and their controls in two
               wetland‐adapted tree species (Alnus glutinosa and Betula
               pubescens) located in a temperate forested wetland. Soil and
               herbaceous plant‐mediated CH4 emissions from hollows and
               hummocks also were measured, thus enabling an estimate of
               contributions from each pathway to total ecosystem flux. Stem
               CH4 emissions varied significantly between the two tree species,
               with Alnus glutinosa displaying minimal seasonal variations,
               while substantial seasonal variations were observed in Betula
               pubescens. Trees from each species emitted similar quantities of
               CH4 from their stems regardless of whether they were situated in
               hollows or hummocks. Soil temperature and pore‐water CH4
               concentrations best explained annual variability in stem
               emissions, while wood‐specific density and pore‐water CH4
